    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-18T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="1049"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1049">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890E.01/5–1845: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-18T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >May 18, 1945—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2763. Chauvel took careful note of the message contained in Department’s 2104,
                    May 16, but remarked that he had not seen any offer <pb facs="1093" n="1081"
                        xml:id="pg_1081"/> from the British for “the simultaneous progressive
                    withdrawal of both French and British troops from the Levant States”. The
                    British Prime Minister in his letter to de Gaulle had spoken of a withdrawal of
                    British troops “at the moment a treaty has been concluded and is in operation
                    between the French Government and the Syrian and Lebanese Governments”.</p>
                <p>Duff Cooper when approached in connection with the Department’s telegram was very
                    vague and had nothing new to offer.</p>
                <p>As reported in my 2522, May 11,<note n="13" xml:id="d1049fn13">Not
                        printed.</note> he told me then that the Prime Minister<note n="14"
                        xml:id="d1049fn14">The British Prime Minister.</note> was feeling much more
                    cheerful about the whole business.</p>
                <p>Sent Department as 2763, repeated to Beirut as 19.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
